ARCHIVE SERIAL: #001-020796
ANNOUNCEMENT DATED: 02.July 1996 19:24EDT [FGADM.01-DM]

ATTN all Flight Gear FS developers and list participants

This is to officially welcome you to the Flight Gear Development family.
Anytime you see this letterhead, you will know that official business
is being announced. In any case, I would like to take this time to ask
your cooperation in our first big steps into getting this simulator
off the ground. (Pardon the pun) :)

I've noticed that list activity has slowed to almost nothing in the
past month or so, so I thought I'd send this out to try to get us
back on track. Up until now, we've mostly just been unorganized,
sending in code and miscellaneous announcements and examples. This
approach is fine initially, but I feel we're in need of more organization
to manage time, coordinate group communication, and the writing of
actual code. 

Below, I've appended a "skeleton" list of groups that need to be created:

* Administration
	Keeps everyone on task and is the "central power" that
	all groups report to.
* Archives Department
	Stores all announcements and code (basically everything)
	that is related to the FGFS project.
* Programming (specific subdivisions included)
	- Kernel module: writes and hashes out issues concerning the
	  core of the simulator and maintains updates of the kernel
	  (similar to the Linux project) once the simulator is publicly
	  released.
		SUGGESTED GROUP PARTICIPANTS:
			* Curt Olson
			* Maurizio Gavioli
			* Eric Korpela
	- Visuals/graphics: writes routines that relate to the visual
	  display of objects in the simulator.
		SUGGESTED GROUP PARTICIPANTS:
			* ???
	- User interface: handles issues concerning the graphical
	  user interface of the simulator.
	- Wx generation: writes code and resolves issues concerning the
	  retrieval of real-time weather and the display of the wx.
	  Will coordinate heavily with the visuals team.
		SUGGESTED GROUPS PARTICIPANTS:
			* Curt Olson
			* ?
	- ATC development: talking, interactive, SMART air traffic control.

	- Scenery: hashes out issues dealing with the display of scenery,
	  in the respect of file structure and level of detail, etc.
		SUGGESTED GROUP PARTICIPANTS:
			* Maurizio Gavioli
			* ?
	
	- Aircraft Visual Modeling: Will basically be a subdivision of
	  the scenery and visuals team. Determines how an aircraft will
	  be represented (in terms of file structure, texture display,
	  etc.)
	- Motion/flight modeling: Will create and or implement equations
	  /code to accurately model flight on the computer.
		** This team must keep in mind that 100% realism is NOT
		   THE most important factor. We must also consider frame
		   rate, and find a happy medium between calculation and
		   graphic display/refresh rates.

These are all of the groups that I can think of at the moment, but
you are certainly free to add to these in any way you see fit.
Now that we know WHAT we need to do, we now need to decide WHO is
going to be in these groups. As you can see, I have listed certain
people as "suggested" on the basis of what they have done for
Microsoft Flight Simulator. They and anyone else is/are certainly welcome
to be on any team they wish. I have "appointed" myself to be a part
of the administration team, since my programming ability (especially in
C) is not advanced enough to be of any help in this project. 

Shmuel Ben-Artiz (I apologize for spelling errors that I may have made
in any of y'alls names :) has suggested that we have a liason in 
every team that will communicate with other teams that the administration.
The admins will periodically post an annoucement to this list stating
what each team is working on and where to download their work to take
a look at it. 

I think that, when we are finally ready for our first public release,
we should have a pre-compiled version of everything for those that
have no interest in tinkering with the code. Or, if the person
is in an adventurous state of mind :) they can download all the code.

Another point is, are we going to have different distributions of this
simulator? (Again, like the Linux project) Obviously, people are going
to be publishing custom modules, and perhaps a radically different 
simulator in the end. Will we official update a standard kernel every
so often, or will this be up to each distribution's management? 

In any case, this simulator MUST REMAIN FREE OF CHARGE forever! That
is the original goal of this program in the first place. I believe we
are going by the GNU license? 

Our next problem is: in what language do we write this? I strongly 
suggest C, as this is the native language of the bulk of our programmers.
I think we have decided on DJGPP for the DOS and Linux versions?
What compiler will we use for Windows95? Let's say right off, that we're
going to avoid Visual Basic completely. VB is simply too slow for the 
kind of work that this simulator is going to require. 
Microsoft Visual C++ perhaps?

My opinion is: we should work on the DOS version first, then on to
Windows95, and then port it to Linux and whatever other operating
systems we see fit. DOS is what MOST people in "our target market"
 are using right now, even though the architecture is a little old. 
Win95 seems to be the "wave of the future" <groan>, so I suppose that 
will be next.

In addition to all this, I'd like to bring up another issue...
where do we get the data for realistic terrain/geography plotting?

Let me know, and let's come up with the other issues that need to
be confronted! I'm looking forward to responses... let's go ahead
and decide what groups we're going to be in! :)

Regards,
David Murr

PS: I'll explain the archives codes and all that in a little bit... :)
