Robert Epps writes:
> I think I will unsub too, but for a different reason:  I think this
> project is drifting way off course.

It's a shame to see people leave, but we are at a point right now
where not to many people can contribute.  We need to get a basic sim
with an open architecture up and running before lots of people will
jump on the band wagan.  Flight-Gear is a great idea, but we haven't
moved too far forward yet.

For any who are considering leaving this list, I wish you the best in
all your future endevours.  Please check in on us once in a while.  

> I presume the whole reason for getting FS enthusiasts together to
> write a freeware flight simulator is to make the BEST simulator money
> can't buy, not just a MFS clone.  But the MFS clone is where this
> project seems to be headed; you all are aiming way too low!

This is, and will always be the goal.  However, we cannot achieve this
instantly.  We must build up to it incrementally.  I think MSFS
compatibility is a worthy first step.  It would give us access to a
huge amount of scenery.  There's no reason why we can't support .bgl
format while also developing a much better format.

> Well then, BLOW OFF the 486!!!  Why does Flight Gear have to run on
> your grandmother's four-year-old machine?

Unfortunately, a lot of us still have 486's.  I was thinking of
upgrading to a Cyrix 5x86 120 this month, but it doesn't look like its
going to happen this summer.

> I want to see a flight simulator with a realistic flight model and
> realistic scenery, with lots of buildings, telephone poles, bridges,
> trees, moving cars on the streets, etc. -- not just a few textured
> cubes and triangles plunked down on a flat painted landscape.  I
> think many others want that too.

Like I said before, this is a great target to shoot towards.  However,
we are all doing this in our spare time as a hobby.  We need to bite
off chunks we can chew.  Once we get going though, with enough people
chewing, we just might get there.

> This project probably has a year at least before it produces even the
> beginnings of an actual running simulator.  By then, $1500 computers
> at K-Mart will be 200 MHz Pentiums with MMX extensions (or Macs with
> 150 MHz PowerPC 604 chips).  I think that nothing less than a 90 MHz
> Pentium, running a real multithreaded OS like Windows 95 or NT or OS/2
> or Linux, should be the target for Flight Gear -- it's not supposed to
> be an FS clone, but the best flight simulator for serious enthusiasts!
> Don't let ridiculously low platform requirements cripple it.

Now's a great time to buy a computer, hopefully in a year it will be
even better.  However, someone with a 486 isn't going to be too
excited about writing software they can't run.  I think if we can
write a simulator that runs acceptably on a 486, we will be much
better off when running on higher end machines.  We will have much
more room to add even cooler features (every byte of code slows things
down just a bit.)

We will all have different goals and ideas about what FlightGear
should be.  My "vision" is for FlightGear to be a common framework
upon which we can all pursue our own directions, goals, and ideas,
while at the same time cooperating so our work benifits everyone.

Curt.
