Well, I typed a big long eloquent reply to this, it took me nearly an
hour, then just before I clicked on the "send" button, Netscape
crashed and blew it all away.  So here's the short, humorless version
(sent from Agent this time!):

I think the main message I am trying to get across is that time needs
to be taken to make sure that the world model and 3D engine have no
arbitrary limits to the number, complexity and density of the polygons
and textures.  None of this "gee there's no way any computer is going
to handle an airplane made out of 10000 textured polygons, so let's
make our data structure simple by limiting each 3D object to 16
polygons" crap.  Maybe your 486/50 can't handle it, but in two years,
your Octium MegaPro/300 will fly through that much detail at 60 frames
per second and beg for more.  The key word here is SCALEABILITY.
Flight Simulator has blocky, jagged, sparse terrain regardless of
whether you run it on a 486/33 or Pentium/200, because it does not
have that degree of scaleability -- the data is built the lowest
common denominator platform.  Don't make the same mistake with FG!

        --- Rob

