Curt,

>It's a shame to see people leave, but we are at a point right now
>where not to many people can contribute.  

That *may* be true within the tight confines of developing flight models. I
wouldn't presume to wade into the morass of mathematical calculations, 3
DOF/6 DOF trade-offs, reality vs. plausibility compromises, etc. in that area.

But that's not the whole picture. The flight model will not exist as an
island apart. It will have to be part of a total approach that will involve
scenery design, interactive ATC interfaces, cross-platform considerations,
programming objects to make possible the design of all forms of
instrumentation and flight control needed for realistic flight control,
advanced panel designs. The list goes on.

>We need to get a basic sim
>with an open architecture up and running before lots of people will
>jump on the band wagan.  Flight-Gear is a great idea, but we haven't
>moved too far forward yet.

The basic architecture will have to include as much as possible of the
"goodies" which will make up a fully integrated system before it will
develop much enthusiasm. If we want to entice more causal simmers into
becoming serious sim enthusiasts (and this is a requirement if our project
is to become more than just the "toy of the elite few") then everything must
fit together from the beginning into a seamless, user-friendly (don't you
just hate that term) environment.

>> I presume the whole reason for getting FS enthusiasts together to
>> write a freeware flight simulator is to make the BEST simulator money
>> can't buy, not just a MFS clone.  But the MFS clone is where this
>> project seems to be headed; you all are aiming way too low!
>
>This is, and will always be the goal.  However, we cannot achieve this
>instantly.  We must build up to it incrementally.  I think MSFS
>compatibility is a worthy first step.  It would give us access to a
>huge amount of scenery.  There's no reason why we can't support .bgl
>format while also developing a much better format.

Please keep in mind that FS-compatible and FS clone are not necessarily the
same thing. I think that you and Robert are really arguing two sides of the
same coin here. We don't need to create a MS-lookalike in order for it to be
operationally compatible with FS.

>Unfortunately, a lot of us still have 486's.  I was thinking of
>upgrading to a Cyrix 5x86 120 this month, but it doesn't look like its
>going to happen this summer.

When will FG be ready to beta, let alone to "market" (yes, I know that it'll
be freeware). Next week? Next month? *Maybe* next year. And the decisions
regarding platforms and technologies have to be made with those
considerations in mind. If you only have a 486 available and you want to
test out some advanced graphics concepts that are only practical on high-end
machines, then I'm sure that someone on the list will find a way to make the
services of one available to you for that purpose (just as long as you don't
need a Cray 2B).

But that's one of the reasons that we will also need as part of our team one
or two people who are adept at reading cybermarket trends and can produce
reliable "guesstimates" (how's that for an oxymoron) about what hardware and
software technologies will be *broadly available* and *commonly in use* by
the projected release time.

>> I want to see a flight simulator with a realistic flight model and
>> realistic scenery, with lots of buildings, telephone poles, bridges,
>> trees, moving cars on the streets, etc. -- not just a few textured
>> cubes and triangles plunked down on a flat painted landscape.  I
>> think many others want that too.
>
>Like I said before, this is a great target to shoot towards.  However,
>we are all doing this in our spare time as a hobby.  We need to bite
>off chunks we can chew.  Once we get going though, with enough people
>chewing, we just might get there.

And that's one of the reasons for attracting as broad a talent base as
possible from the beginning. There's no reason that part of the team can't
already be looking at how Phase I can easily transition into Phase II right
from the start.

>We will all have different goals and ideas about what FlightGear
>should be.  My "vision" is for FlightGear to be a common framework
>upon which we can all pursue our own directions, goals, and ideas,
>while at the same time cooperating so our work benifits everyone.

Very true, Curt. And I would think that one of the responsibilities of the
admin group would be to keep the broad picture in view so that each
individual in each specialized group doesn't have to constantly relate their
own work to other fields that they possibly don't have a great deal of
expertise in. Thus the work of the programmers can be melded with the work
of the aeornautical theoreticains, the designers of broad sceneries, the
specialists in major airports, the panel designers, the creators of
adventures, and so on. 

Perhaps it will develop that there will be a number of lists like this, each
devoted to specialized aspects of the overall package. Perhaps the process
will develop along the lines of a whole new paradigm in small group/large
group team efforts. Whatever, the end result must be to make it possible to
maximize the efforts of each individual "technician" by allowing them to
apply themself fully to their own area of expertise.

Basically, what I'm saying in this response is that everything that you've
said is valid and makes perfect sense in the restricted context in which you
said it. But I'm also arguing for a look at the broader picture.

Shalom,

Shmuel


