Sorry it took me so long to respond to this.  I apparently get to
spend most of my summer with bronchitis.  The groups idea is great.
Sign me up for the Administration, Kernel, and Visuals/graphics
group.  (It's pretty much what I've been doing anyway.)

> is the original goal of this program in the first place. I believe we
> are going by the GNU license? 

Yes, as far as I'm concerned.  

> Our next problem is: in what language do we write this? I strongly 
> suggest C, as this is the native language of the bulk of our programmers.
> I think we have decided on DJGPP for the DOS and Linux versions?
> What compiler will we use for Windows95? Let's say right off, that we're
> going to avoid Visual Basic completely. VB is simply too slow for the 
> kind of work that this simulator is going to require. 
> Microsoft Visual C++ perhaps?

For windows 95 we could use the Win-32 version of GCC, but I think that's
up to the windows programmers to standardize on.  (I think it's available
from the Cygnus ftp site.) For OS/2, I think that EMX is the way to go.

> My opinion is: we should work on the DOS version first, then on to
> Windows95, and then port it to Linux and whatever other operating
> systems we see fit. DOS is what MOST people in "our target market"
>  are using right now, even though the architecture is a little old. 
> Win95 seems to be the "wave of the future" <groan>, so I suppose that 
> will be next.

Agreed, but I think that concurrent development is possible, in that
all routines should be as platform independent as possible.  All of my code
to date will run on DJGPP, EMX, Sunos, and Linux/ELF.  I intend to keep
everything I write that way.  (I still haven't gotten the entire demo package 
together, but I'm working on it slowly but surely.  Any volunteers wishing
to help, raise your hands. Especially Mac/Windows programmers)  For DOS, I'm 
only up to 320x200 graphics, but I hope to expand that to 640x480 soon.

I looked at jlib, and there are some good ideas there that I may coopt into
the demo package, but as a whole the library has a few snags.  I'm also
not sure it's license is compatible with the GPL, so I may have to reverse
engineer the good parts.

Eric
