Hi guys,

Lately I've been playing around with ACM on my Linux box.  ACM stands
for Air Combat Maneuvers.  It is a free (src included) flight sim for
Unix/X.  If any of you are interested in looking at this, check out:

    ftp://ftp.netcom.com/pub/ra/rainey/acm/index.html

After playing around with this sim for a while, I have concluded that
it represents a significant amount of work, and is a very worth-while
program.

I have a little proposal for you all to consider.  I propose that we
base our Flight Gear project off of this product.  I have put some ACM
screen shots up on the new flight gear web page:

    http://www2.me.umn.edu/~clolson/fgfs


Some of the current features of ACM are:

  - Freeware -- all source code included.
  - Pretty good flight model that can be tailored to different kinds
    of aircraft / missles / flying things.
  - Sound support (with some pretty descent sound effects).
  - Allows definition of new planes.
  - U.S. Navy Postgraduate School's Distributed Interactive
    Simulation (IEEE DIS, RFC <something or other>) code integrated
    into it.  This allows multiple ACM servers to talk to each other
    over local subnets.  You can go 2 vs. 2 over a network.
    This also allows you to integrate with other simulation packages that
    use this same standard.  (i.e. a tank simulation, or ATC simulation or
    whatever.)
  - Some serial-port joystick support
  - Currently has a nice rendition of the Hawaiian Islands based on DEM data.
  - Has distance visibility effects (haze).
  - Models springiness of landing gear.
  - Has a very nice HUD display.
  - Has an HSI on the instrument panel.


Features in the upcoming version (due out real soon now):

  - True spheroidal world.
  - Scene descriptions in latitude/longitude/MSL-height coordinates.
  - Automated extracts of scene descriptions from the FAA databases.
  - Support for a non-zero feet MSL surface height.
  - NAVAID support for the features listed above.


Weaknesses:

  - Terrain modeling has room for improvement in the area of hidden surface
    removal and shading.
  - Usability -- no menus and such.
  - Scenery object descriptors are pretty primitive.
  - Code is not structured well for modularity.
  - Currently only supports Unix/X11
  - Saying the representation of the instrument panel is crude would
    be heaping undeserved praise upon said instrument panel.  Although it
    does have an HSI which FS5/6/7/... still lacks.
  - Scenery is pretty scarce.
  - Although it does have a single overcast cloud layer, this is the
    totallity of it's weather modeling.
  - Currently only support X11 for graphics.


Comments:

Civilian vs. Military:

ACM is currently focused towards military combat, but it does come
with a Cesna 172 airplane.  Slap on a censa inst. panel, and add some
scenery and we would already be pretty close to FS4 functionality.
Although it would be a bummer to have an F-18 swoop down and knock you
out of the sky on your way from Souix City, IA to Des Moines ... :-)


Cooperating with Riley Rainey and the ACM devel team:

Ideally, we would join forces and work together with the ACM devel
team.  However, integrating our efforts with the ACM devel team might
prove to be difficult.  This is Riley Rainey's program and he does
most of the work on it.  I don't mean this in a negative way at all.
He wrote the program, he should be able to manage and control it's
development in any way that suits him.  I wrote a freeware check book
balancer and know exactly how he feels.  On the down side, Riley is
currently very busy with his real job and doesn't have a lot of time
to put into acm.  The pieces of the source are not very modular, so it
currently would be difficult to have multiple people working on it at
the same time.

One option, would be to take the current source, or wait for the soon
to be released version, and branch off in our own direction.  This
would be fine, as long as we adhere to the GNU general public license
under which ACM is licensed.

We could split everything apart into logical modules (we have
previously discussed various breakdowns.)  From that point we could
just start going to it.


Then what:

Initially, we would want to carefully separate out the generic
graphics routines from the system specific graphics routines, and
organize things so we can easily port to new graphics systems.  Then
we could try to port the rest of it (or as much of the rest of it as
possible) to DOS.  We would want to look at how scenery and objects
are represented.  We would want to add real instrument panels, and
look at adding more joystick and sound support.

I think all the weaknesses which I previously addressed are very
addressable ... especially if we can modularize the code so we can all
work on different sections concurrently.


Then what:

By now we have a kick butt, world famous flight simulator.  Microsoft,
already devestated by the Caldera/Dr. DOS lawsuit, watches sales of
it's last best money making hope (FS6) dwindle.  Meanwhile, Bill Gates
baracades himself in his office as the forces of good close in on all
sides ... ok, I'll stop before any physical harm befalls Bill and I
lose my "G" rating.


So,

Check out the screen shots, have a look at the ACM home page, if you
can and if you want to, compile and run ACM, then let me know what you
think about this idea.

Thanks,

Curt.
